canonical:
  title: 謝發還漂海人表
  author: 無名氏
  language: lzh
  text: 天心字小克敦撫綏海曲覃恩冞深感激佩銘曷已糜粉難酬伏念臣幸際昌辰叨居弊服唯知謹於屛翰曾未補於涓埃豈意漂風之船獲依上國之岸特紆睿鑑之顧再造餘生俾及賤价之回復還舊業歡騰鄕井事光簡編玆蓋伏遇大度包荒至仁育物保萬民而如子德侔乾坤合四海以爲家澤洽夷夏遂令遐裔偏荷殊私臣謹當恪守箕封庶殫釐東之職恒申華祝倍輸拱北之誠
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 謝發還漂海人表
  author: 無名氏
  language: lzh
  text: 天心字小。克敦撫綏。海曲覃恩。冞深感激。佩銘曷已。糜粉難酬。伏念臣幸際昌辰。叨居弊服。唯知謹於屛翰。曾未補於涓埃。豈意漂風之船。獲依上國之岸。特紆睿鑑之顧。再造餘生。俾及賤价之回。復還舊業。歡騰鄕井。事光簡編。玆蓋伏遇大度包荒。至仁育物。保萬民而如子。德侔乾坤。合四海以爲家。澤洽夷夏。遂令遐裔。偏荷殊私。臣謹當恪守箕封。庶殫釐東之職。恒申華祝。倍輸拱北之誠。
korean:
  title: 표류인을 돌려보내 주신 데 대해 사례하는 글
  author: 무명씨
  language: kor
  text: 폐하께서 작은 나라를 사랑하시어 도탑게 위무하시고 바닷가에까지 은혜가 미치니, 더욱 깊이 감격하여 금석에 새긴들 그만두겠으며 몸이 가루가 된들 갚을 수 있겠습니까.공손히 생각하니, 신은 다행히 좋은 때를 만나 외람되이 누추한 땅에 거하여, 오직 속국의 예절을 닦을 줄만 알고, 일찍이 티끌만큼도 도우지 못하였습니다. 그런데 뜻밖에 표류한 배가 중국의 언덕에 표착하여 특별히 폐하께서 돌보심에 힘입어 남은 목숨을 살려주시고 우리 사신이 돌아오는 편에 딸려보내어 다시 옛 보금자리로 돌아오게 하시니, 기뻐함이 고향에 가득하고 일이 사책(史冊)에 빛납니다. 이것은 대개 폐하께서 큰 도량이 거친 것을 포용하시고, 지극한 인(仁)으로 만물을 길러서 만백성을 보호하기를 자식같이 여기심이요, 덕이 천지와 같아 사해를 한 집안으로 삼고, 혜택이 외국과 중국에 흡족하여서 드디어 먼 지방 사람으로 하여금 넓고 특수한 은혜를 입게 하심을 만난 것입니다. 신이 삼가 마땅히 기봉(箕封)을 정성껏 지켜서, 동방을 다스리는 직분을 다하고, 항상 화축(華祝)을 올려 폐하께 향하는 정성을 배나 바치겠습니다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0410_010_0390&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: A Memorial of Gratitude for the Return of Castaways
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your Majesty's compassion extends to the smallest nations,
    Your nurturing care touches even the curved shores of the sea.
    Our hearts overflow with deepest gratitude—
    Could we inscribe it in stone, it would never cease,
    Could we grind ourselves to dust, we could never repay.

    I humbly reflect: by fortune's grace, I have witnessed this auspicious age,
    Unworthy though I am to dwell in these humble lands.
    I know only to preserve the rites befitting a tributary state,
    Yet I have contributed not even a speck of dust to your glory.

    Who could have foreseen that our drifting vessels,
    Cast adrift upon the waves, would find haven upon your shores?
    Through your sovereign regard, our remnant lives were restored,
    And our envoys returned home bearing us with them,
    Back to our ancestral nest—our joy overflows through our valleys,
    Our deeds now shine in the pages of history.

    This flows from your boundless magnanimity,
    Your supreme benevolence that nourishes all beings,
    You shelter the ten thousand peoples as your own children,
    Your virtue mirrors heaven and earth alike.
    You embrace the four seas as one household,
    Your grace flows equally to distant lands and the Middle Kingdom.
    Thus have we remote peoples received such singular favor.

    I pledge to faithfully guard my sacred duties,
    To fulfill my responsibility as keeper of the eastern realm,
    To offer perpetual blessings and unceasing devotion,
    Bowing ever northward with redoubled sincerity.
  footnotes:
    - This is a formal memorial (表) submitted by a tributary state expressing gratitude for the imperial court's benevolence in returning shipwrecked sailors. The specific country is not named in the text.
    - The phrase '箕封' (Qi feng) refers to the sacred trust or mandate of governance over a region.
    - The expression '拱北' (gong bei, 'bowing northward') is a poetic way of expressing submission and loyalty toward the emperor in Beijing.
